The paper deals with security and resilience in Networks on Chip (NoCs), which are a type of embedded system. The focus is on side-channel attacks, which are a type of cryptographic attack that can be used to infer secret information by analyzing non-functional properties of the system. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with real-time systems, which are a type of embedded system that have strict timing requirements. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Embedded Systems (cs.ET) sub-category. The paper also deals with the design and optimization of NoCs, which suggests that it may belong to the Architecture (cs.AR) sub-category. The paper uses evolutionary optimization techniques, which suggests that it may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the impact of security mechanisms on real-time performance guarantees, which suggests that it may also belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category.
